subSubSection.paragraph:
Descriptions. 
Larva.

CUTICULAR COLORATION. Dorsal side of head and thorax brown, either unicolor or with few diffusive lighter areas (
Fig. 105
). Cuticle of legs unicolor brown. Abdominal terga brown, either unicolor, or with diffusive lighter areas; sterna lighter, unicolor. Tergalii ocher or light brown (
Figs 100–104
). Caudalii unicolor light brown (
Fig. 108
).

STRUCTURE. Body relatively slender. Frons between antennae bases flat and bordered by pair of ridges; frontal suture blunt-angled (as in 
Fig. 72
). Distal margin of frons sharply projected above clypeus (as in 

P. camerunense

).

Paraglossae larger than glossae, both glossae and paraglossae widened distally (
Figs 95, 96
). Glossa with regular row of long setae on inner margin (
Fig. 96
). Both glossae and paraglossae apically-ventrally with numerous irregularly situated long setae, apically-dorsally with row of larger setae (
Fig. 96
; as in 
Fig. 34
). Glossa with 2–4 long setae on distal half of dorsal side; paraglossa with one long seta on distal half of dorsal side (
Fig. 95
). Distal segment of labial palp [formed by fusion of 2nd and 3rd primary segments—see 

Pseudopannota

(8)] widest at middle; its inner-apical margin bears irregular row of setae; outer and ventral surfaces soft and densely covered with numerous irregularly situated soft colorless setae (
Fig. 96
).

Mesonotum with antero-lateral corners projected anteriorly (
Fig. 105
). Fore protoptera not fused (
Fig. 20
). Vestiges of hind protoptera absent. Coxa of each leg with rounded or pointed lobe, subequal on legs of all pairs (
Figs 111, 112
). Fore femur thickest proximally, middle and hind femora parallel-sided. Outer margin of each femur with irregularly situated stout setae; besides it, distal part of anterior surface with few setae of the same structure: 2–3 on fore femur (
Fig. 111
), 1 on middle femur (
Fig. 112
), absent on hind femur. 
No
structures resembling femoral patch of Baetofemorata. Tibiae and tarsi with few stout spine-like setae on inner side. Patellatibial suture equally developed on all legs. Each claw, besides apical hook, always with two diverging denticles, larger proximal one and smaller distal one (
Figs 23, 24
).

Surface of abdominal terga and sterna with pointed denticles and scales in wide semicircular sockets; on anterior segments scales sparse (
Fig. 106
), on posterior segments dense (
Fig. 107
). Posterior margin each tergum I– X with regular short denticles (
Figs 106, 107
). Sterna I–VI with posterior margin entirely smooth, sterna VII and VIII with very small denticles on posterior margin, sternum IX with denticles on posterior margin. Paraprocts with many short marginal denticles (
Fig. 108
).

Tergalii (
Figs 100–104
) elongate, with costal margin nearly straight and anal margin convex; margin entirely bordered by thin rib, densely or sparsely serrate; at distance from costal margin and parallel to it, locates wide additional rib projected dorsally. Surface of tergalius without scales; with pointed denticles (similar to denticles on surface of tergum) either on whole dorsal surface of tergalius, or only on dorsal surface of its additional rib; tracheae dense, either partly pigmented and visible, or entirely invisible. Tergalius I several times smaller than others (
Fig. 100
), tergalii II–VI subequal, tergalius VII smaller.

Cerci nearly as long as body, paracercus twice shorter. Segments of cerci and paracercus with equally small triangular denticles on posterior margins (
Fig. 108
).

TEXTURE. On fore leg of male 1st–4th tarsomeres covered by blunt microlepides, 5th tarsomere covered by pointed microlepides; on other legs of male and all legs of female all tarsomeres covered by pointed microlepides (see 
Table 2
).
